    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Salacia articulata</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_4599",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Colonial hydroid with stiff, upright, orange-brown stems, each bearing paired lateral branches of decreasing length that lie in a single plane (the whole resembling a child’s drawing of a Christmas tree!). Both the main stem and side branches bear polyps of both sides and the slipper-like hydrothecae, from which these emerge, are sunken into the stem. If present, reproductive individuals (gonothecae) are urn-shaped with a wide aperture and are born in clusters near the main stem.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_4600",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Polyps less than 1 mm, stems typically 30 mm tall, but up to 60 mm reported, gonothecae up to 3 mm.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_4601",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Some sources give this species as endemic to Southern Africa (including Vema Seamount), but WORMS lists it as widespread across both north and South Atlantic Oceans. The taxonomy remains confused and northern records may in fact represent an undescribed species (see reference below)</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Whole region, from intertidal to 135 m.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_4602",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Widely distributed on rocky reefs, and in sheltered pools where it forms dense colonies, particularly in S. W. Cape.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_4603",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Presumed to feed on small particles and planktonic organisms in the water.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_4604",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Colonies spread asexually by putting up new stems from the creeping ‘roots’. There are separate males and females and fertilized eggs develop within the female gonothecae to form planula larvae.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_4605",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Distinctive stiff, flat appearance is unusual, but easily confused with members of the closely-related genus <i>Sertularella</i> which have similar colony form, but the polyps are borne in hydrothecae that project from the sides of the stems, rather than being sunken into them.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_4606",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa (Fourth edition). Struik Nature, Cape Town (p. 54).<br><br>Day, JH (1969). A Guide to Marine Life on South African Shores. A.A. Balkema, Cape Town (p. 28).<br><br>Jones, G (2008). A Field Guide to the Marine Animals of the Cape Peninsula. SURG, Cape Town (p. 58).<br><br>Millard, NAH (1975). Monograph on the Hydroida of Southern Africa. <i>Annals of the South African Museum</i>, 68, 1-513 (p. 273).<br><br>Moura, CJ, Cunha, MR, Porteiro, FM & Rogers, AD (2011). The use of the DNA barcode gene 16S mRNA for the clarification of taxonomic problems within the family Sertulariidae (Cnidaria, Hydrozoa). <i>Zoologica Scripta</i>, 40(5), 520-537.",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_4607",
